pipeline {

    agent any

    tools {
        nodejs 'NodeJS'
    }

    stages {

        stage('Checkout') {
            steps {
                git branch: 'main',
                url: 'https://github.com/Krish9505/Playwright-API-Automation.git'
            }
        }

        stage('Install Dependencies') {
            steps {
                bat 'npm install'
            }
        }

        stage('Install Playwright Browsers') {
            steps {
                bat 'npx playwright install'
            }
        }

        stage('Run API Automation') {
            steps {
                bat 'npx playwright test'
            }
        }
    }
}
Step 5 — Push Jenkinsfile to GitHub
git add .
git commit -m "Added Jenkins pipeline"
git push
Step 6 — Configure Jenkins

Open Jenkins.

Create New Item

Choose:

Pipeline
Step 7 — Pipeline Configuration

Inside Jenkins job:

Under Pipeline

Choose:

Pipeline script from SCM

SCM:

Git

Repository URL:

https://github.com/Krish9505/Playwright-API-Automation.git

Branch:

*/main

Script Path:

Jenkinsfile

Save.

Step 8 — Build

Click:

Build Now
Difference Between Jenkinsfile and YAML
Jenkins	GitHub Actions
Uses Groovy	Uses YAML
Jenkinsfile	.github/workflows/*.yml
Runs in Jenkins server	Runs in GitHub
So For Your Case
Jenkins → Use
Jenkinsfile
GitHub Actions → Use
.github/workflows/playwright.yml
Industry Standard

Most companies use:

Jenkinsfile

inside repository.

That is called:

Pipeline as Code
Final Flow
VS Code
   ↓
Create Jenkinsfile
   ↓
Push to GitHub
   ↓
Jenkins Reads Jenkinsfile
   ↓
Runs Playwright Automation